data.content:
Use EF Core 7+'s **`ExecuteUpdateAsync`** and **`ExecuteDeleteAsync`** — they translate directly to SQL `UPDATE`/`DELETE` statements without loading anything into memory:

```csharp
// Operation 1: Bulk update — single UPDATE statement
await _db.Products
    .Where(p => p.LastSoldDate < DateTime.UtcNow.AddMonths(-6))
    .ExecuteUpdateAsync(s => s.SetProperty(p => p.IsActive, false));

// Operation 2: Bulk delete — single DELETE statement
await _db.AuditLogs
    .Where(l => l.CreatedAt < DateTime.UtcNow.AddYears(-1))
    .ExecuteDeleteAsync();
```

**Why this is fast:**
| | Old approach | New approach |
|---|---|---|
| SQL roundtrips | 2 (SELECT + UPDATE/DELETE per row) | 1 single statement |
| Memory | Loads 500K/2M entities | Zero entities loaded |
| Change tracker | Tracks every entity | Bypassed entirely |

**Generated SQL is essentially:**
```sql
UPDATE Products SET IsActive = 0 WHERE LastSoldDate < @cutoff;
DELETE FROM AuditLogs WHERE CreatedAt < @cutoff;
```

**Caveats:**
- These bypass the change tracker — any cached entities won't reflect the change
- No `SaveChangesAsync()` needed (or wanted)
- If 2M deletes cause lock escalation/timeouts, batch with a loop:

```csharp
int deleted;
do
{
    deleted = await _db.AuditLogs
        .Where(l => l.CreatedAt < DateTime.UtcNow.AddYears(-1))
        .Take(10_000)
        .ExecuteDeleteAsync();
} while (deleted > 0);
```
